{
  "text": "Intrinsic feature variability depends on the set of classes that features have to discriminate. Most frequently considered classes are phonemes or phonetic features. Feature variability causes ambiguities in classifying speech signal segments. Ambiguities can be reduced by using different feature streams. A single feature stream can be obtained from different streams. In [CITATION_1] , a sub-optimal solution is proposed for selecting features from two different sets. Other approaches integrate some specific parameters into a single stream of features [CITATION_2] . Without attempting to find an optimal set of acoustic measurements, many recent automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems combine streams of different acoustic measurements ( [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] ). In [CITATION_5] it is shown that log-linear interpolation provides good results when used for integrating probabilities computed with acoustic models with different feature sets. Another possibility [CITATION_6] consists in combining the results of ASR systems in order to reduce word error rates (WER). In this paper, the possibility is considered to use multi-model systems for predicting feature variability as described in section 2. A solution is presented in section 3. Using variability indicators as diagnosis features, the possibility of predicting when it is potentially useful to use a new set of features is discussed in section 4. Results with a programmable use of a multi-feature system are presented in Section 5.",
  "citation_candidates": [
